Step 6 – Linux Logs & Troubleshooting

Goal: Learn how to find the root cause of issues using logs instead of guessing.

Reality in DevOps:
When a production server goes down, your manager won't ask:

"Do you know Linux?"

They'll ask:

"What do the logs say?"

Learning to read logs is one of the most valuable Linux skills you can develop.

🎯 Learning Objectives

By the end of this step, you'll be able to:

Understand what logs are.
Know where Linux stores logs.
Use journalctl effectively.
Read application logs.
Search and filter logs.
Monitor logs in real time.
Troubleshoot common production issues.
1. What are Logs?

A log is a record of events generated by the operating system or an application.

Examples:

User logged in
SSH login failed
Nginx started
Docker crashed
Disk became full
Application threw an exception

Think of logs as a black box recorder for your server.

2. Where Are Logs Stored?

Most traditional logs are stored under:

/var/log

View them:

ls -lh /var/log

Typical output:

/var/log
├── syslog
├── auth.log
├── kern.log
├── dpkg.log
├── apt
├── nginx
├── apache2
├── journal
3. Important Log Files
Log File	Purpose
/var/log/syslog	General system events (Ubuntu)
/var/log/auth.log	Authentication & SSH logins
/var/log/kern.log	Kernel messages
/var/log/dpkg.log	Package installation history
/var/log/nginx/access.log	HTTP requests
/var/log/nginx/error.log	Nginx errors
/var/log/boot.log	Boot process
/var/log/apt/history.log	APT installation history
4. View Logs

Entire file:

cat /var/log/syslog

Usually better:

less /var/log/syslog

Navigation:

Space → Next page
b → Previous page
/error → Search
q → Quit
5. View Last Lines

Most troubleshooting starts here:

tail /var/log/syslog

Last 50 lines:

tail -50 /var/log/syslog
6. Watch Logs Live

One of the most useful commands:

tail -f /var/log/syslog

Now open another terminal and execute commands.

You'll immediately see new log entries.

Stop:

Ctrl + C
7. Search Logs

Search for errors:

grep ERROR /var/log/syslog

Ignore case:

grep -i error /var/log/syslog

Search SSH:

grep ssh /var/log/auth.log
8. Count Matches

Example:

grep ssh /var/log/auth.log | wc -l

Useful for quick analysis.

9. journalctl

Modern Linux uses systemd journal.

View all logs:

journalctl

Current boot:

journalctl -b

Previous boot:

journalctl -b -1
10. Logs for a Service

Example:

journalctl -u nginx

Recent entries:

journalctl -u nginx -n 30

Follow live:

journalctl -u nginx -f
11. Filter by Time

Last hour:

journalctl --since "1 hour ago"

Today:

journalctl --since today

Specific time:

journalctl --since "2026-07-18 09:00"
12. Find Boot Errors
journalctl -p err -b

Priority levels:

Level	Meaning
emerg	Emergency
alert	Immediate action
crit	Critical
err	Error
warning	Warning
notice	Notice
info	Information
debug	Debug
13. Monitor Authentication

Failed logins:

grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log

Successful logins:

grep "Accepted password" /var/log/auth.log
14. Package History

See what was installed:

cat /var/log/dpkg.log

APT history:

cat /var/log/apt/history.log
15. Log Rotation

Imagine logs growing forever.

Eventually:

500 GB log file 😱

Linux solves this using logrotate.

Configuration:

/etc/logrotate.conf

Additional configs:

/etc/logrotate.d/

Log rotation:

Compresses old logs
Creates new log files
Deletes very old logs
Practical Lab (45–60 Minutes)
Task 1

List log files:

ls -lh /var/log
Task 2

View the last 20 lines:

tail -20 /var/log/syslog
Task 3

Watch logs:

tail -f /var/log/syslog

Open another terminal:

sudo apt update

Observe new log entries.

Task 4

Search authentication logs:

grep ssh /var/log/auth.log
Task 5

View Nginx logs:

journalctl -u nginx
Task 6

Restart Nginx:

sudo systemctl restart nginx

Immediately check:

journalctl -u nginx -n 20
Task 7

Find boot errors:

journalctl -p err -b
Task 8

Find package installation history:

cat /var/log/apt/history.log
Real DevOps Scenario
Problem

Users report:

"Website is down."

What should you do?

Step 1
systemctl status nginx
Step 2
journalctl -u nginx -n 50

Suppose you see:

Permission denied
Step 3

Check configuration:

sudo nginx -t
Step 4

Fix the configuration.

Step 5

Restart:

sudo systemctl restart nginx
Step 6

Confirm:

systemctl status nginx

This is a structured troubleshooting approach instead of restarting services blindly.

Biggest Mistakes Engineers Make
❌ Mistake 1

Restarting services without checking logs.

Always inspect the logs first.

❌ Mistake 2

Using cat on huge log files.

Prefer:

tail
less
grep
journalctl

These are faster and more practical.

❌ Mistake 3

Ignoring warnings.

Today's warning can become tomorrow's outage. Review recurring warnings before they escalate.

